# CLINE RULES - TOKEN OPTIMIZED

## Output

- No greetings, transitions, or summaries.
- No explanation of what changed unless asked.
- No inline code comments unless the logic is non-obvious.
- Keep prose responses under 20 words.

## File Handling

- Never read a file unless it is directly required for the current edit.
- Never print the full content of an unchanged file.
- Use targeted SEARCH/REPLACE edits only. No full file rewrites.

## Plan Mode

- Output a flat checklist of files to modify and the change type.
- Do not ask clarifying questions mid-task. Make a reasonable assumption and state it in one line.

## Act Mode

- Execute edits directly. No narration.
- Do not re-read files already in context.

## Code Standards

- Strict types, explicit error handling, modular structure.
- Run compile/test command once before marking task complete if config exists.

## Tool Discipline

- Batch all terminal commands into one shell call where possible.
- Do not verify a file write by re-reading it immediately after.
- Do not run `ls` or `find` to explore structure — ask if uncertain.
- Do not attempt to install global CLI tools. Run compile checks with npx tsc --noEmit only.

## Error Handling

- On error, fix it directly. Do not ask for permission to retry.
- Do not re-attempt the same fix more than twice. State the blocker instead.

## Scope Control

- Only touch files explicitly mentioned or directly required.
- Do not refactor, rename, or reformat anything outside the task scope.
- Do not introduce new dependencies unless asked.
- When adding functions to an existing file, append only. Do not rewrite existing functions.

## Assumptions

- If intent is ambiguous, make the most conservative assumption and state it once.
- Do not pause mid-task to ask clarifying questions.
